{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1723"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.27,0.04,0.36,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112298"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1723"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94348"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112298"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents with epigastric pain after a night out at a restaurant. The pain started shortly after a meal and she also felt nauseated. She has never had any similar pain before.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a CT scan of the abdomen as part of investigation, which showed gallstones in her gallbladder. In addition to the gallstones the CT scan has shown a 6 cm solid mass in the upper pole of the left kidney which enhances. The investigation is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management for the incidental finding on imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Do nothing","Repeat scan in six months","Abdominal ultrasound","CT-guided biopsy","Left nephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis fits the description for a medium-sized renal cell carcinoma (4 - 7 cm) and there does not appear to be any evidence of tumour spread. Providing the patient is otherwise fit, she should be counselled for a nephrectomy. For T1 tumours \u0026lt;7cm, a partial \u003Cstrong\u003Enephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is inappropriate to \u003Cstrong\u003Edo nothing\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat the scan in six months\u003C/strong\u003E as this mass is six centimetres now and could grow or spread over that time. It is inevitable that nephrectomy is required. If the tumour was defined as a small (\u0026lt;3cm) tumour, then the patient could be kept under observation. This might particularly be the case for the older, unfit patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide any additional information to the CT scan, thus, is not an appropriate next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETissue diagnosis via \u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not required in this patient due to the size of the tumour; first line management is nephrectomy which will allow for tissue diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with large renal carcinoma that has not metastasised, nephrectomy is first-line treatment."],"references":["Gray RE, Harris GT. Renal Cell Carcinoma: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019; 99:179-84. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2019; 99:732.","Powles T, Albiges L, Comperat E, et al. Renal cell carcinoma: ESMO Clinical Practice Guideline for diagnosis, treatment and follow-up. Ann Oncol. 2019; 30:706-20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94348"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-28T17:50:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T17:50:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1723"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112298"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/121"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Renal cell carcinoma","synonyms":["RCC"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30